pgTitle: List of tornadoes in the Super Outbreak

rows.text: Tornado unroofed or destroyed several homes.
1 death - Tornado struck northwest side of Decatur, destroying 35 homes and damaging 120. Near-F4 damage reported. Figure of 26 injuries only represent patients hospitalized.
Tornado hit and damaged a local high school. Also heavily damaged homes in western Bismarck.
Not listed as F2 tornado by some authorities.
1 death - Tornado produced minor property damage.
Tornado unroofed a home and damaged six others at Greenback.

3 deaths - Tornado passed through southern Etowah, destroying 23 homes and killing two people in trailers. One additional death elsewhere. Tornado damaged or destroyed 37 homes in McMinn County alone.
Tornado hit southeastern Nashville, causing significant damage to large homes, trailers, and businesses. May have been an F3 rather than an F2 tornado due to severity of damage.
Tornado produced high-end F3 damage to three homes.
Tornado mostly hit forested land but caused F2 damage.
10 deaths - Tornado destroyed as many as 50 homes near Cookeville, killing 10 people in the vicinity. One person injured in the tornado died a month later.
5 deaths - Tornado caused all five deaths and destroyed homes at Moodyville before crossing the Tennessee-Kentucky border.
7 deaths - Tornado injured 150 people and destroyed 48 homes in four separate subdivisions near Jamestown. All seven deaths occurred in the four subdivisions.
3 deaths - Tornado destroyed two subdivisions in northwest Livingston. Damaged more than 275 homes and destroyed 50 homes and trailers each. All three deaths occurred in trailers.
Tornado tore apart two trailers and other buildings. Also damaged a dozen additional homes.
Tornado destroyed 11 or more homes along with three businesses, 16 barns, and 18 trailers. Was an F3 tornado according to some sources.
2 deaths - Tornado struck a mobile home park, damaging or destroying multiple homes.
1 death - Tornado killed one woman as it destroyed a home. Majority of damage was reported on farms. Parent thunderstorm later produced the Hamburg tornado.
Numerous homes and mobile homes heavily damaged in Swayzee.
Eight homes suffered extensive damage and two mobile homes were destroyed.
Destroyed one warehouse, grain bins, and trailers.

2 deaths - Formed from the same thunderstorm that spawned the Sayler Park tornado, with the first damage seen in northern Cincinnati. Some homes in Mason were completely leveled. Was the last in a series of five violent F4‑F5 tornadoes spawned by the same storm, beginning in southwest Indiana.
Caused damage to 20 homes and destroyed a home along with three barns.
Destroyed one home, a garage, and two barns.
1 death - Destroyed one house and the barn. Also hit and destroyed four other homes and small buildings. One woman killed as she attempted to seek cover in her basement.
Destroyed five mobile homes and a barn.
Destroyed two barns and a mobile home.
F4 damage was noted to a home south of Caneyville.
This is a secondary storm that followed the Louisville storm. 18 were injured and the path width was similar to that of the first event.
Most of Mannsville was heavily damaged or destroyed. A total of 50 homes and 60 barns destroyed along the entire track, including 40 homes in Mannsville. 56 people injured.
10 deaths - Tornado struck several communities in Clinton County. Eight of the 10 fatalities occurred in that county. Over 50 homes damaged or destroyed.
40 homes and 75 barns were destroyed. 27 people were injured.
Some sources list up to two deaths, but none are listed officially.
In Mercer County four homes were destroyed and 60 homes were damaged.
Several buildings were destroyed in southern Fayette County.
Listed as an F1 tornado by some sources.
2 deaths - Tornado caused 16 injuries. Some sources indicate three deaths rather than two.
Tornado damaged 20 homes and unroofed a motel near Whitley City.
Tornado destroyed at least a dozen homes along its path.
1 death - Crossed into Georgia where numerous homes were destroyed.
20 people were injured in the storm while numerous trailers and mobile homes were destroyed.
Only tornado of the outbreak in Mississippi. Destroyed a home and 30 farm buildings, killing 15,000 chickens. Also damaged 33 other buildings and a trailer.
Minor damage to the business district of the town.
Sources:Storm Data for April 3, 1974, Grazulis (1974), National Weather Service
